\subsection{Number of detectable subhalos}
The VL-II halo provides a model of the Milky Way, but it cannot capture the orientation of the Galactic disk, much less the specific location of the Earth within this simulated halo. A realistic assumption is that the Galactic disk should be coinciding with the plane perpendicular to the major axis of the dark matter halo. Because the $z$-direction in VL-II is roughly coincident with the major axis of the halo, we assume the Galactic plane to be corresponding to $z = 0$. To generate multiple realisations of the dark matter subhalo population around Earth, we placed the observer at 8.5 kpc (roughly the distance from the Galactic center to Earth) from the center of the halo and rotate it around this point in the $x, y$-plane, keeping the distance to the Galactic center constant. 

